,Recommended,314560,17330934,"Posted: 1 August, 2015",all,ANG3LIC,"I am a believer of giving credit where credit is due, firstly this mainly 2 person dev team did an amazing job with visuals,music and loactions, It really shows what passionate people can do. I dont believe in praising graphics when the game is mind numbing boring which isnt the case with Kyn.Commanding a 2 man team and at some point a 6 man team may seem difficult at 1st but once you adjust to it you will pull of some really amazing wins. Its a mix of diablo hordes (all enemies are beautifully done) and orignal Dugeon siege (Not the god awful Dugeon siege 3). For the most part combat flows, instead of pausing you have a slow motion meter to issue commands, it would have been nice to be giving a pause or slow mo option but i can see what the dev's were trying to do. The ai isnt the best and regulary my melee guys would run after enemies in the opposite direction and unless you issue commands they will stand while being owned by the enemy horde of the moment.BUT these are small complaints on a very soild foundation, the dev's are ACTUALLY listening to the buyers and patching the game regulary. You may get about 15-25 hours depending on difficulty, exploration and side quests. For only 20 Dollars its a steal. I would highly recommand it to anyone interested in this genre."
76561197983239144,Not Recommended,314560,18923583,"Posted: 6 November, 2015",all,Lurker,"I can't in any good conscience recommend this game, though it pains me to say it.  I wanted it to be good.The best measuring stick against an isometric dungeon crawler like this is classic Dungeon Siege (2002).  However, I'm sorry to have to say that Dunegon Siege, while being thirteen years old at this point, is still by far the better experience.Rather than go into a lengthy pseudo-professional game review, I'll just gloss over the worst points of this game:The narrative is pretty messy.  What little narrative there is, anyway.  Admittedly, one does not enter into a game such as Kyn or Dungeon Siege looking for fantastic narrative.  But what Kyn offers is justterrible.The GUI is very un-intuitive and sloppy.  Plenty of functions or features are not visible on the base screen by default.  By this I mean that you cannot, for example, order your caster to heal while also ordering your front-liner to use his wave attack, because the caster's skills only show up on your screen while you are micro-managing him, which you can't do while you are micro-managing your front-liner.  And you can't pause the game to go back and forth between characters to issue commands (see below).On the whole, the game is poorly optimized and doens't flow smoothly.  It feels like a small dev team built it in somebody's basement.  The menus and in-game prompts aren't very obvious or smooth, as one should rightfully expect.Basic functions such as Party Formation, Party UI, Party AI, and Pause Game are entirely overlooked.  If any of these functions exist in the game, they were not easy to find and/or use.  After nearly every battle, my party members were scattered around, and short of me manually putting them into formation, they would remain in their scattered state as I ordered them to move on.  This made it very difficult to proceed through tight areas or to be ready for the next encounter.Whereas in Dungeon Siege you could pause the game with Spacebar, in Kyn you are restricted to 'slowing down time' for a short duration.  A blue meter ticks down rapidly while the monsters continue to bear down on your dying front-liner.  This 'feature' feels like a failed gimmick meant to replace the Pause Game feature with something with more flavor.  It doens't.The graphics are poor, overall.  Granted, with most isometric RPGs you don't expect much when you look closely.  But with Kyn, you are constantly being bombarded with very dated and ugly rendering.If you are looking for an isomentric, dungeon-crawling RPG, just get Dungeon Siege.  You can get it on Steam by purchasing the Dungeon Siege III package, which comes with a free copy of DS I and II."
